00:35:51.022 --> 00:35:53.750
If people stop buying what we're selling.

509
00:35:57.742 --> 00:35:58.909
Jared.

510
00:36:00.182 --> 00:36:02.910
You cannot be doing
what you're thinking of doing.

511
00:36:02.982 --> 00:36:04.466
Well. I don't see any other choice.

512
00:36:04.542 --> 00:36:05.950
What does that mean.
we don't have a choice?

513
00:36:06.022 --> 00:36:07.101
Fuck you. you don't have a choice.

514
00:36:07.182 --> 00:36:10.381
Fuck me?
Did you even look at the numbers. Sam?

515
00:36:10.382 --> 00:36:11.861
Yeah. but what do I know?

516
00:36:11.862 --> 00:36:13.270
Correct me if I'm wrong. Mr. Shah.

517
00:36:13.342 --> 00:36:15.661
but these numbers. they don't add up.

518
00:36:15.662 --> 00:36:17.102
One and one no longer makes two.

519
00:36:17.182 --> 00:36:18.860
Look. if I may.
I would like a little bit more time.

520
00:36:18.861 --> 00:36:20.181
Jared. we can't tell you yet.

521
00:36:20.182 --> 00:36:22.428
Are you fucking kidding me?
We have talked about this.

522
00:36:22.429 --> 00:36:24.790
We need a little more time
to give you our conclusion.

523
00:36:24.791 --> 00:36:27.347
Okay. We meet again in 45 minutes.

524
00:36:27.821 --> 00:36:30.189
- Sam. do you have the file?
- Yeah.

525
00:36:46.741 --> 00:36:48.705
What are you going to do?

526
00:36:51.342 --> 00:36:53.186
Are you gonna call him?

527
00:36:57.702 --> 00:36:59.185
I already have.

528
00:37:13.421 --> 00:37:14.545
Jesus.

529
00:37:18.861 --> 00:37:20.585
Wow. that's gorgeous.

530
00:37:29.501 --> 00:37:31.226
It's a long way down.

531
00:37:32.061 --> 00:37:33.382
Yes. it is.

532
00:37:44.620 --> 00:37:46.748
Will. don't do that. Come on.

533
00:37:49.741 --> 00:37:51.508
You know the feeling that people experience

534
00:37:51.509 --> 00:37:55.385
when they stand on the edge like this
isn't a fear of falling.

535
00:37:55.460 --> 00:37:57.861
It's the fear that they might jump.

536
00:37:58.541 --> 00:38:01.422
That's very deep and depressing.
Thank you.

537
00:38:01.500 --> 00:38:03.660
Yeah. well. I'm a little dark sometimes.

538
00:38:03.661 --> 00:38:05.985
All right. Come down. please. Will.
Please. come on.

539
00:38:06.060 --> 00:38:07.304
Will.

540
00:38:07.581 --> 00:38:09.021
Yeah. fuck it.

541
00:38:11.940 --> 00:38:13.261
Not today!

542
00:38:19.981 --> 00:38:22.305
It looks like they're going to
make us dump this shit.

543
00:38:22.500 --> 00:38:23.547
What?

544
00:38:24.341 --> 00:38:25.740
You watch.

545
00:38:25.741 --> 00:38:26.865
How?

546
00:38:27.501 --> 00:38:28.659
You'll see.

547
00:38:28.660 --> 00:38:30.099
How could they do that?

548
00:38:30.100 --> 00:38:32.828
They can't. It's impossible.
But they'll figure a way.

549
00:38:33.100 --> 00:38:34.748
I've been at this company for 10 years.

550
00:38:34.749 --> 00:38:37.948
and I've seen things you wouldn't believe.

551
00:38:38.660 --> 00:38:41.267
When all is said and done.
they do not lose money.

552
00:38:41.340 --> 00:38:43.980
They don't mind if everybody else does.

553
00:38:44.060 --> 00:38:45.828
but they don't lose.

554
00:38:53.780 --> 00:38:54.860
Will?

555
00:38:56.100 --> 00:38:59.179
Did you really make
two and a half million last year?

556
00:38:59.180 --> 00:39:00.501
Yeah. sure.

557
00:39:03.660 --> 00:39:05.580
How did you spend it all?

558
00:39:06.020 --> 00:39:07.384
It goes quite quickly.

559
00:39:07.459 --> 00:39:09.302
You know.
you learn to spend what's in your pocket.

560
00:39:09.303 --> 00:39:10.860
Two and a half million goes quickly?

561
00:39:10.940 --> 00:39:12.784
All right. let's see.

562
00:39:12.860 --> 00:39:14.899
So the taxman takes half up front.

563
00:39:14.900 --> 00:39:16.263
so you're left with one and a quarter.

564
00:39:17.100 --> 00:39:19.378
My mortgage takes another 300 grand.

565
00:39:19.379 --> 00:39:22.587
I send 150 home for my parents.
you know. keep them going.

566
00:39:22.660 --> 00:39:23.859
- So what's that?
- 800.

567
00:39:23.860 --> 00:39:25.104
All right. 800.

568
00:39:25.940 --> 00:39:27.664
Spent 150 on a car.

569
00:39:28.380 --> 00:39:32.308
About 75 on restaurants.
Probably 50 on clothes.

570
00:39:33.419 --> 00:39:36.339
- I put 400 away for a rainy day.
- That's smart.

571
00:39:36.340 --> 00:39:39.821
Yeah. as it turns out.
'cause it looks like the storm's coming.

572
00:39:40.499 --> 00:39:42.027
You still got 125.

573
00:39:43.939 --> 00:39:48.380
Yeah. well. I did spend $76.520
on hookers. booze. and dancers.

574
00:39:48.459 --> 00:39:50.107
But mainly hookers.

575
00:39:51.259 --> 00:39:52.460
76.5007

576
00:39:53.259 --> 00:39:55.387
I was a little shocked initially.
but then I realized

577
00:39:55.459 --> 00:39:58.699
that I could claim most of it back
as entertainment. it's true.

578
00:40:03.940 --> 00:40:05.107
- Holy shit!
- Goddamn!

579
00:40:05.180 --> 00:40:07.907
The cavalry is here!
Come on. we should go.

580
00:40:14.499 --> 00:40:16.060
How old are you?

581
00:40:17.619 --> 00:40:19.224
- 43.
- Jesus.

582
00:40:24.819 --> 00:40:26.423
This is bizarre.

583
00:40:28.778 --> 00:40:30.787
It's like a dream.

584
00:40:34.619 --> 00:40:38.667
I don't know. seems like we actually
may have just woken up.

585
00:40:41.258 --> 00:40:42.338
Come in.

586
00:40:43.659 --> 00:40:45.142
How do we look?

587
00:40:45.818 --> 00:40:48.306
- I should go.
- No. You should stay.

588
00:40:48.379 --> 00:40:49.503
So?

589
00:40:50.139 --> 00:40:51.857
It's legit.

590
00:40:51.858 --> 00:40:53.463
The kid killed it.

591
00:40:54.139 --> 00:40:56.300
The formula's worthless.

592
00:40:56.378 --> 00:40:58.223
- What does that mean?
- It's broken.

593
00:40:59.179 --> 00:41:02.103
There are eight trillion dollars of paper
around the world

594
00:41:02.179 --> 00:41:03.706
relying on that equation.

595
00:41:03.778 --> 00:41:05.022
Well. we were wrong.

596
00:41:05.099 --> 00:41:07.303
No. you mean you were wrong.

597
00:41:07.378 --> 00:41:09.419
Now. don't get me started.
We discussed this.

598
00:41:09.499 --> 00:41:10.546
I'm heading for the conference room.

599
00:41:10.618 --> 00:41:12.058
No. I want you to hear this.

600
00:41:13.978 --> 00:41:15.857
I don't want to hear this.

601
00:41:15.858 --> 00:41:19.186
How do you think I've stuck around
this place so long?

602
00:41:26.378 --> 00:41:27.818
I called Tuld.

603
00:41:30.298 --> 00:41:32.186
Do we have a contingency plan here?

604
00:41:32.187 --> 00:41:34.382
- A contingency plan?
- Yes.

605
00:41:34.738 --> 00:41:36.986
No. we went all in on this one.

606
00:41:38.058 --> 00:41:41.505
So we've gotten ourselves
quite exposed here. haven't we?

607
00:41:43.498 --> 00:41:45.507
To Tuld or the market?

608
00:41:47.338 --> 00:41:48.626
To both.

609
00:42:10.498 --> 00:42:11.981
He's here?

610
00:42:41.457 --> 00:42:44.456
- Tuld's helicopter just landed.
- I know. Come with us.

611
00:42:44.457 --> 00:42:46.541
- Where's Sam?
- I don't know. You sure you want all of us?

612
00:42:46.617 --> 00:42:47.784
Yes.

613
00:42:53.777 --> 00:42:57.137
One piece of advice for everyone
before we go in there.

614
00:42:57.657 --> 00:42:59.185
This could get a little ugly.

615
00:42:59.257 --> 00:43:01.657
But whatever you do. just tell the truth.
No sugarcoating

616
00:43:01.737 --> 00:43:03.176
Do not change a word of it.

617
00:43:03.177 --> 00:43:06.779
No one here is smart enough.
including the rocket scientist.

618
00:43:13.417 --> 00:43:15.501
- Mr. Cohen.
- Morning.

619
00:43:17.297 --> 00:43:18.857
This way. please.

620
00:43:23.537 --> 00:43:25.740
He's already in there waiting for you.

621
00:43:25.817 --> 00:43:27.018
Excellent.

622
00:43:49.576 --> 00:43:50.656
John.

623
00:43:51.977 --> 00:43:53.581
Please. sit down.

624
00:43:56.296 --> 00:43:57.944
Welcome. everyone.

625
00:43:58.017 --> 00:44:00.624
I must apologize for dragging you all here
at such an uncommon hour.

626
00:44:00.696 --> 00:44:04.864
But from what I've been told. this
matter needs to be dealt with urgently.

627
00:44:04.936 --> 00:44:07.860
So urgently. in fact. it probably
should have been addressed weeks ago.

628
00:44:07.936 --> 00:44:10.097
But that is spilt milk under the bridge.

629
00:44:10.176 --> 00:44:14.181
So. why doesn't somebody tell me
what they think is going on here?

630
00:44:15.136 --> 00:44:17.744
Mr. Tuld. as I mentioned earlier.

631
00:44:17.816 --> 00:44:20.500
if you compare the figure
at the top of page 13...

632
00:44:20.576 --> 00:44:23.980
Jared. it's a little early for all that.
Just speak to me in plain English.

633
00:44:25.216 --> 00:44:26.255
Okay.

634
00:44:26.256 --> 00:44:28.297
In fact. I'd like to speak to
the guy who put this together.

635
00:44:28.376 --> 00:44:30.699
Mr. Sullivan. is it? Does he speak English?

636
00:44:30.776 --> 00:44:32.020
Sir?

637
00:44:32.096 --> 00:44:33.656
I'd like to speak with the analyst

638
00:44:33.736 --> 00:44:35.263
who seems to have
stumbled across this mess.

639
00:44:35.336 --> 00:44:38.260
Certainly. That would be Peter Sullivan.
Right here.

640
00:44:38.336 --> 00:44:40.497
Oh. Mr. Sullivan. you're here.
Good morning.

641
00:44:40.575 --> 00:44:43.215
Maybe you could tell me
what you think is going on here.

642
00:44:43.216 --> 00:44:47.100
And please.
speak as you might to a young child

643
00:44:47.175 --> 00:44:49.575
or a golden retriever.

644
00:44:49.576 --> 00:44:53.177
It wasn't brains that got me here.
I can assure you of that.

645
00:44:57.175 --> 00:45:00.176
Well. sir. as you may or may not know.
I work

646
00:45:00.256 --> 00:45:03.660
here for Mr. Rogers as an associate
in the Risk Assessment

647
00:45:03.736 --> 00:45:05.574
and Management Office at MBS.

648
00:45:05.575 --> 00:45:09.177
Please. Just relax. Stand up.
Tell us in a clear voice.

649
00:45:09.255 --> 00:45:11.536
What is the nature of the problem?

650
00:45:13.576 --> 00:45:14.623
Okay.

651
00:45:16.295 --> 00:45:19.654
As you probably know.
over the last 36 to 40 months

652
00:45:19.655 --> 00:45:22.743
the firm has begun packaging

653
00:45:22.815 --> 00:45:27.736
new MBS products that
combine several different tranches

654
00:45:27.815 --> 00:45:30.936
of rating classifications
in one tradable security.

655
00:45:31.815 --> 00:45:33.895
This has been enormously profitable.

656
00:45:33.896 --> 00:45:36.024
as I imagine you noticed.

657
00:45:36.096 --> 00:45:37.263
I have.

658
00:45:37.455 --> 00:45:39.584
The firm is currently doing
a considerable amount

659
00:45:39.655 --> 00:45:40.660
of this business every day.

660
00:45:40.735 --> 00:45:44.494
Now the problem. which is. I guess.
why we are here tonight.

661
00:45:44.495 --> 00:45:47.496
is that is takes us. the
firm. about a month

662
00:45:48.015 --> 00:45:52.174
to layer these products correctly.
thereby posing a challenge

663
00:45:52.175 --> 00:45:54.378
from a Risk Management standpoint.

664
00:45:54.615 --> 00:45:56.383
And. Mr. Sullivan. that challenge is?

665
00:45:56.775 --> 00:46:00.814
We have to hold these assets on our books
longer than we might ideally like to.

666
00:46:00.815 --> 00:46:01.982
Yes.

667
00:46:02.055 --> 00:46:04.782
But the key factor here is
these are essentially just mortgages.

668
00:46:04.855 --> 00:46:08.613
So that has allowed us to push
the leverage considerably beyond

669
00:46:08.614 --> 00:46:12.139
what you might be willing or allowed to do
in any other circumstance.

670
00:46:12.215 --> 00:46:16.023
thereby pushing the risk profile
without raising any red flags.

671
00:46:17.694 --> 00:46:19.419
Now... Thank you. Mr. Sullivan. Sit down.

672
00:46:19.495 --> 00:46:21.818
What I'm guessing your report here says.

673
00:46:21.895 --> 00:46:24.219
and give me some rope here.

674
00:46:24.294 --> 00:46:28.135
What I'm guessing it says is that
considering the. shall we say.

675
00:46:28.215 --> 00:46:31.259
bumpy road we've been on
the last week or so.

676
00:46:31.335 --> 00:46:35.974
that the figures your brilliant co-workers
up the line ahead of you have come up with

677
00:46:36.009 --> 00:46:38.253
don't make much sense any more

678
00:46:38.254 --> 00:46:40.655
considering what's taking place today.

679
00:46:40.734 --> 00:46:42.414
Actually. not what's taking place today.

680
00:46:42.415 --> 00:46:45.142
but what's already taken place
over the last two weeks.

681
00:46:45.215 --> 00:46:48.455
So. you're saying
this has already happened?

682
00:46:48.534 --> 00:46:49.854
Sort of.

683
00:46:51.255 --> 00:46:52.455
Sort of.

684
00:46:53.614 --> 00:46:58.142
And. Mr. Sullivan. what does your model
say that. that means for us here.

685
00:46:59.294 --> 00:47:01.782
Well. that's where it becomes a projection.

686
00:47:02.014 --> 00:47:03.181
But...

687
00:47:05.414 --> 00:47:07.978
You're speaking with me. Mr. Sullivan.

688
00:47:08.374 --> 00:47:09.738
Well. sir.

689
00:47:10.374 --> 00:47:14.093
if those assets decrease by just 25%

690
00:47:14.094 --> 00:47:15.981
and remain on our books.

691
00:47:16.574 --> 00:47:20.622
that loss would be greater than
the current market capitalization

692
00:47:20.694 --> 00:47:22.538
of this entire company.

693
00:47:25.894 --> 00:47:28.742
So. what you're telling me

694
00:47:30.254 --> 00:47:33.374
is that the music is about to stop

695
00:47:34.613 --> 00:47:37.657
and we're going to be left
holding the biggest bag

696
00:47:37.734 --> 00:47:39.022
of odorous excrement

697
00:47:39.293 --> 00:47:41.901
ever assembled in the history of

698
00:47:43.693 --> 00:47:45.057
capitalism.

699
00:47:48.934 --> 00:47:53.014
Sir. I'm not sure that I would put
it that way. But let me clarify.

700
00:47:53.533 --> 00:47:55.653
Using your analogy.

701
00:47:55.654 --> 00:47:57.454
what this model shows

702
00:47:58.493 --> 00:48:01.221
is the music. so to speak. just slowing.

703
00:48:02.534 --> 00:48:04.812
If the music were to stop. as you put it.

704
00:48:04.813 --> 00:48:07.978
then this model wouldn't be even close
to that scenario.

705
00:48:08.054 --> 00:48:10.661
It would be considerably worse.

706
00:48:14.533 --> 00:48:17.141
Let me tell you something. Mr. Sullivan.

707
00:48:18.133 --> 00:48:22.542
Do you care to know why
I'm in this chair with you all?

708
00:48:22.613 --> 00:48:24.937
I mean. why I earn the big bucks?

709
00:48:26.213 --> 00:48:27.173
Yes.

710
00:48:27.254 --> 00:48:30.374
I'm here for one reason
and one reason alone.

711
00:48:30.853 --> 00:48:36.701
I'm here to guess what the music might do
a week. a month. a year from now.

712
00:48:37.973 --> 00:48:39.261
That's it.

713
00:48:40.093 --> 00:48:41.217
Nothing more.

714
00:48:43.493 --> 00:48:45.577
And standing here tonight.

715
00:48:46.373 --> 00:48:51.741
I'm afraid that I don't hear a thing.

716
00:48:54.333 --> 00:48:55.500
Just

717
00:48:57.852 --> 00:48:59.336
silence.

718
00:49:14.492 --> 00:49:18.497
So. now that we Know the music has
stopped. what can we do about it?

719
00:49:19.252 --> 00:49:21.413
Mr. Cohen? Ms. Robertson?

720
00:49:22.773 --> 00:49:26.254
I'm afraid I think this is where
you're supposed to step back in.

721
00:49:26.692 --> 00:49:30.053
Lord knows we've relied enough
on Mr. Sullivan tonight.

722
00:49:31.652 --> 00:49:33.661
What do you have for us?

723
00:49:41.293 --> 00:49:45.297
What have I told you since
the first day you stepped into my office?

724
00:49:46.172 --> 00:49:48.976
There are three ways to make a living
in this business.

725
00:49:49.052 --> 00:49:52.293
be first. be smarter. or cheat.

726
00:49:53.172 --> 00:49:54.852
Now. I don't cheat.

727
00:49:55.332 --> 00:49:59.576
And although I like to think we have
some pretty smart people in this building.

728
00:50:00.172 --> 00:50:03.577
it sure is a hell of a lot
easier to just be first.

729
00:50:04.332 --> 00:50:06.057
Sell it all. Today.

730
00:50:08.772 --> 00:50:10.780
Is that even possible. Sam?

731
00:50:11.252 --> 00:50:13.096
Yes. but at what cost?

732
00:50:14.812 --> 00:50:16.372
I'll have to pay.

733
00:50:18.052 --> 00:50:19.491
Really?

734
00:50:19.492 --> 00:50:20.855
I think so.

735
00:50:22.012 --> 00:50:24.260
Where is this going to come back to us?

736
00:50:25.012 --> 00:50:26.059
Everywhere.

737
00:50:26.851 --> 00:50:31.260
Sam. I don't think you seem to understand
what your boy here has just said.

738
00:50:34.851 --> 00:50:36.456
If I made you.

739
00:50:37.212 --> 00:50:38.859
how would you do this?

740
00:50:44.492 --> 00:50:47.580
You call the traders in for their normal
6:30 meeting and you be honest with them.

741
00:50:47.652 --> 00:50:50.052
Because they're going to know
it's the end either way.

742
00:50:50.252 --> 00:50:53.132
You're going to have to throw them a bone.
and a pretty big one.

743
00:50:53.211 --> 00:50:55.535
And then you've got to
come out of the gates storming.

744
00:50:55.612 --> 00:50:57.772
No swaps. No nothing.

745
00:50:57.851 --> 00:51:00.055
40% done by 10:15. By 11:00.

746
00:51:00.131 --> 00:51:01.570
all your trades have to be gone

747
00:51:01.571 --> 00:51:03.895
because by lunchtime.
word's going to be out.

748
00:51:04.851 --> 00:51:08.810
And by 2:00 you're going to be selling
at 65 cents on the dollar. if you're lucky.

749
00:51:08.811 --> 00:51:11.692
And then the feds are going to be in here.
up your ass. trying to slow you down.

750
00:51:11.771 --> 00:51:12.938
Ramesh?

751
00:51:13.011 --> 00:51:15.530
They can slow you down.
They can't stop you.

752
00:51:15.531 --> 00:51:16.810
It's yours to sell.

753
00:51:16.811 --> 00:51:18.895
But. John. even if

754
00:51:19.811 --> 00:51:22.931
we manage to pull that off.
and that's saying something.

755
00:51:24.451 --> 00:51:27.331
the real question is.
who are we selling this to?

756
00:51:27.811 --> 00:51:30.299
Same people we've been selling it to
the last two years.

757
00:51:30.371 --> 00:51:31.970
and whoever else will buy it.

758
00:51:31.971 --> 00:51:34.219
But. John. if you do this.

759
00:51:35.570 --> 00:51:38.419
you will kill the market for years.
